    <h2>JAMB Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details>
      <summary>8. How can I download the JAMB syllabus?</summary>
      <p>
        The JAMB syllabus is an essential guide that outlines the topics you are expected to study for each subject. To download the syllabus:
        <br /><br />
        <strong>Official Method:</strong><br />
        Visit the official JAMB website at <a href="https://www.jamb.gov.ng" target="_blank">https://www.jamb.gov.ng</a>.<br />
        Navigate to the <em>“Syllabus”</em> section. Select your subject and download the syllabus in PDF format.
        <br /><br />
        <strong>Alternative Method:</strong><br />
        You can also search online for <em>“JAMB 2025 Syllabus PDF download”</em> to find it on educational blogs. Ensure you use a trusted source.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>9. How many times can I take JAMB?</summary>
      <p>
        There is <strong>no official limit</strong> to how many times you can register for JAMB. You can take the exam every year, as long as you meet the registration requirements such as having valid O’level results and a NIN (National Identification Number).
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>10. Can I change my course or institution after JAMB?</summary>
      <p>
        <strong>Yes</strong>, JAMB allows candidates to change their course or institution after the exam. This process is called the <em>Change of Course/Institution</em> and is typically available once results are released.
        <br /><br />
        To make changes, you’ll need:
        <ul>
          <li>A JAMB profile</li>
          <li>Access to the JAMB portal</li>
          <li>A payment of around ₦2,500</li>
        </ul>
        Be sure to research the new course or institution’s requirements before applying the change.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details>
      <summary>11. What is the minimum score to gain admission?</summary>
      <p>
        The minimum JAMB score required for admission varies by institution and course. However, the general benchmark is:
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Universities:</strong> 160–200</li>
          <li><strong>Polytechnics:</strong> 120–140</li>
          <li><strong>Colleges of Education:</strong> 100–120</li>
        </ul>
        Note that competitive courses like Medicine, Law, and Engineering may require much higher scores. Always check with your chosen institution for their specific cut-off marks.
      </p>
    </details>
